Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_9fa4f592-b726-a731-640e-37c9620ff0ec" anchor="principles" obligation="normative">
<title id="_cc617891-430c-f60a-b8d7-13aa7e181d0b">Principles of measurement for re-entrant (or <asciimath>4pi</asciimath>) ionization chambers</title>
<p id="_3895ded0-ef64-a737-95c5-8680cf4a435f">Ionizing devices have been used since the discovery of x rays by Röntgen in 1895 and of “radio-activity” by Becquerel in 1896, the latter having observed the discharging effects of an electrometer by radiation from uranium <eref type="inline" bibitemid="bec1896" citeas="[17]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="bec1897a" citeas="[18]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="bec1897b" citeas="[19]"/>. The pioneers in developing devices for radiation measurements similar to ionization chambers were Thomson and Rutherford (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="tho1896" citeas="[446]"/>) and Rutherford (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="rut1897" citeas="[360]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="rut1899" citeas="[361]"/>). Elster and Geitel (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="els1897" citeas="[127]"/>) and Owens (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="owe1899" citeas="[329]"/>) also employed quantitative methods with ionizing devices before 1900. A cylindrical vessel, much resembling a re-entrant ionization chamber, is first described by Elster and Geitel (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="els1899" citeas="[128]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="els1902" citeas="[129]"/>) and in improved versions in 1904 and 1905 (see <xref target="fig1a"/>-<xref target="fig1b"/>). It mainly served to measure the radioactivity of “emanation” in air, but also to detect the radioactivity from uranium ore [Elster and Geitel (1899, 1904)]. A similar construction by Wilson (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="wil1900" citeas="[474]"/>) was reported in one of the first textbooks on radioactivity by Rutherford (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="rut1904" citeas="[363]"/>). Two of these early ionization chambers are shown in <xref target="fig2a"/>-<xref target="fig2b"/>. Another early re-entrant ionization chamber of cylindrical form, with about a 10 l volume, for the measurement of sources of radium minerals is described by Bothe (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="bot1915" citeas="[40]"/>), and an improved version with an open well was constructed in 1921 (<xref target="fig3a"/>), published by Fränz and Weiss (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="fra1935" citeas="[153]"/>). Comparable constructions are described by Dorsey (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="dor1922" citeas="[117]"/>) (<xref target="fig3b"/>), Hess and Damon (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="hes1922a" citeas="[205]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="hes1922b" citeas="[206]"/>) and Bothe (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="bot1924" citeas="[41]"/>). To measure ionization currents from those times and until the early 1950s, electrometers or electroscopes of various types were used, see preceding figures and the articles of Curie (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="cur1912" citeas="[87]"/>), Meyer and Hess (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="mey1912" citeas="[308]"/>), Hess (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="hes1913" citeas="[204]"/>), Curtiss (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="cur1928" citeas="[89]"/>), Lauritsen and Lauritsen (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="lau1937" citeas="[273]"/>), Staub (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="sta1953" citeas="[425]"/>), Lindemann and Keely (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="lin1924" citeas="[279]"/>), Geiger and Campion (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="gei1960" citeas="[167]"/>), Price (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="pri1958" citeas="[341]"/>). Quadrant electrometers permit measurements over larger ionization current ranges, see <eref type="inline" bibitemid="dol1901" citeas="[115]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="rut1904" citeas="[363]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="rut1907" citeas="[364]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="swa1921" citeas="[432]"/>. Many facts about the design and the working principles of current ionization chambers appear also in the context of measurements in the fields of dosimetry and radioprotection. Several models of such current ionization chambers can be found as examples in <xref target="fig4a"/>-<xref target="fig4g"/>, but only the type shown in <xref target="fig4g"/> is used for activity measurements in the sense of this review.</p>

<p id="_960eb358-7492-af55-23eb-ef13b40a0ed2">For a basic understanding of charge collection and ionization current characteristics, see <eref type="inline" bibitemid="rut1899" citeas="[361]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="rut1901" citeas="[366]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="rut1902" citeas="[362]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="rut1904" citeas="[363]"/> and <eref type="inline" bibitemid="rut1907" citeas="[364]"/>. More sophisticated descriptions of the ionization process can be found for instance in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="eve1906" citeas="[144]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="eve1911" citeas="[145]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="eve1917" citeas="[146]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="dor1910" citeas="[116]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="mey1927" citeas="[309]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="ros1949" citeas="[357]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="wil1950" citeas="[471]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="sta1953" citeas="[425]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="boa1956" citeas="[29]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="boa1966" citeas="[30]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="ful1958" citeas="[160]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="her1958" citeas="[203]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="pri1958" citeas="[341]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="kme1960" citeas="[257]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="wil1961" citeas="[473]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="kno1989" citeas="[258]"/>.</p>
2



002492techniques
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_f24a1081-dfda-33da-a47c-ebf72b2a6af0" anchor="techniques" obligation="normative">
<title id="_84c58c8c-536e-062c-7df5-e158c10e9347">Techniques of measurement for ionization current</title>
<p id="_e31f6d15-5ba4-4ada-95cd-d8778676f70b">Measurements of small ionization currents in ionization chambers have been used for activity determinations since the early days of the discovery of radioactivity, as notes in <xref target="principles"/>. The currents to be expected range from about 10<sup>–8</sup> A to 10<sup>–13</sup> A, with instrument leakage currents down to a few 10<sup>–15</sup> A. The description of the physical processes (see <xref target="ionization_current"/>) shows that the ionization current in a chamber with a fixed source is produced in a continuous or “stable” manner. The relevant time parameters for a single measurement are usually short in comparison with the half-life of the radionuclide being measured. The occurrence of interactions and charge production is “constant”, apart from small fluctuations due to the statistics of the detection process. The ionization current can therefore be regarded as almost constant during a measurement, apart from the small fluctuations caused by electronic noise and background variations. Particularly stable current sources have been produced by Dalmazzone (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="dal1972" citeas="[94]"/>) and Böhm (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="boh1979" citeas="[36]"/>) (<xref target="fig26"/>) using radioactive sources such as <sup>90</sup>Sr/<sup>90</sup>Y in ionizing devices as reference sources for currents from about 10<sup>–10</sup> A to 10<sup>–14</sup> A. The stability of ionization currents permits the application of quasi-static electronic methods, such as charge integration with large capacitors (up to 100 nF), or compensation procedures continuously following the current production. This keeps the duration of an individual measurement in a range from several tenths of a second to a few hundred seconds, depending on the activity of the source. During a current measurement of the order of magnitude described, leakage and instrument offset currents must be held as low as possible. This completely excludes galvanometric methods, and calls for electrometric methods with insulator resistances above <asciimath>100 "unitsml(TOhm)"</asciimath> <eref type="inline" bibitemid="kei1984-2" citeas="[251]"/>.</p>

<p id="_132773cf-b562-13d5-431e-aa09fa9c03fb">The essential part of a current-measuring system is the electrometer. Today four classes of electrometer are known: electrostatic electrometers (with a mechanical part or indicator driven by electrostatic forces), electronic vacuum-tube electrometers, dynamic condenser electrometers, also called vibrating-reed electrometers (VRE), and solid-state device electrometers. From the early days of radioactivity measurements until the 1950s, the classical electrostatic electrometers were used almost exclusively (see introduction to <xref target="principles"/>). Some of the first instruments with electronic tubes appeared in the 1930s <eref type="inline" bibitemid="jae1929" citeas="[235]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="lea1937" citeas="[274]"/>, and were available until the 1960s with rather sophisticated circuit designs for measurements of high accuracy <eref type="inline" bibitemid="leo1950" citeas="[276]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="hub1954" citeas="[221]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="hub1955" citeas="[222]"/>. Starting from the 1940s, electrostatic electrometers were replaced by vibrating reed electrometers <eref type="inline" bibitemid="pal1947" citeas="[330]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="fas1958" citeas="[149]"/>. Some of these are still in use today <eref type="inline" bibitemid="gui1974" citeas="[193]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="ryt1983b" citeas="[376]"/>, but they are no longer on the market. At present, most electrometers use solid-state device entry stages of high resistance <eref type="inline" bibitemid="neg1967" citeas="[317]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="kei1984-2" citeas="[251]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="kei1992" citeas="[250]"/>. Keithley’s commercial electrometers provide current ranges down to 10<sup>–17</sup> A. Some electrometer properties are explained briefly in <xref target="electrometer"/>.</p>
2



002962_3dbc913d-915a-12ff-981b-3ff7bd02f995
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_3dbc913d-915a-12ff-981b-3ff7bd02f995" obligation="normative">
<title id="_0525952c-2cf4-d0ab-e459-4e3b665640d3">Systematic effects in ionization-current measurements</title>
<p id="_cf4bd380-2eb8-42b1-dac7-648b6f95e77f">Radiation interactions and charge collection in ionization chambers are dominated by statistical processes <eref type="inline" bibitemid="fan1947" citeas="[147]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="fan1954" citeas="[148]"/> which are described more generally in <xref target="ionization_process"/>. The operation of the current-measuring electronics connected to the chamber can be understood in terms of the general theory of integrating ratemeter electronics which was first described by Schiff and Evans (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="sch1936" citeas="[392]"/>) for a charge-integrating device. An analogous expression derived for a counting experiment gives a standard deviation of <asciimath>ii(sigma)_"N" = ii(N)^(–1//2)</asciimath>, where <asciimath>ii(N)</asciimath> is the number of counts measured by a radiation-detector counter chain. A standard deviation of the instrument reading of <asciimath>ii(sigma) = (2x * ii(RC))^(–1//2)</asciimath> was deduced, where <asciimath>x</asciimath> is the average (or expected) number of pulses received per time unit in the device and <asciimath>ii(RC)</asciimath> is the time constant of the integrating capacitor and discharging resistor. Similar descriptions or expressions for integrating devices can be found in Evans (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="eva1955" citeas="[143]"/>), Maier-Leibnitz (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="mai1957" citeas="[289]"/>), Weber (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="web1966" citeas="[464]"/>), Andresen (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="and1967" citeas="[7]"/>), Dörfel (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="dor1967" citeas="[114]"/>) and Weise (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="wei1971" citeas="[466]"/>). An ionization chamber with current measurement corresponds to the special case of a device having a very large time constant <asciimath>ii(RC)</asciimath>.</p>

<clause id="_9136e72b-b855-16f8-59fc-ab60dd9714df" anchor="fluctuations" obligation="normative">

004552radionuclidic_​impurties
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_e0d95715-c466-e76d-4ff9-43e1293a285e" anchor="radionuclidic_impurties" obligation="normative">
<title id="_82587703-36fe-9762-c531-939d04cc7f1b">Radionuclidic impurities</title>
<p id="_d063c3dd-1921-2d2e-4b42-e8b84e129e66">An ionization chamber with a current-measurement system for activity determination is an integrating device which, in principle, picks up all the ionizing radiation which enters its sensitive volume. One single measurement, therefore, does not suffice to distinguish the radiations from the different radionuclides present in the sample. In a radioactive source all radionuclides, except the nominal one and its daughter nuclides, are regarded as impurities. It is obviously very important to check for radionuclidic impurities in a sample and to correct for the contribution of impurity components to the ionization current. Well-known candidates for radionuclidic impurities are <sup>56</sup>Co and <sup>58</sup>Co in <sup>57</sup>Co, <sup>99</sup>Mo in <sup>99</sup>Tc<sup>m</sup>, <sup>124</sup>I in <sup>123</sup>I, <sup>126</sup>I in <sup>125</sup>I, <sup>154</sup>Eu in <sup>152</sup>Eu or <sup>200</sup>Tl and <sup>202</sup>Tl in <sup>201</sup>Tl. For example, if a <sup>57</sup>Co source containing only 0.1% of <sup>56</sup>Co is measured in an ionization chamber and no correction applied, an error of about 1.5% in the nominal activity value of the <sup>57</sup>Co will result <eref type="inline" bibitemid="jed1983" citeas="[240]"/>. Fairly complete lists of probable or possible impurities in standard sources for about fifty radionuclides are given by Jedlovszky and Szörenyi (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="jed1983" citeas="[240]"/>), Rytz (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="ryt1983a" citeas="[375]"/>) and Dryak et al. (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="dry1981" citeas="[119]"/>), with the 2nd revised edition of Dryak et al. (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="dry1981" citeas="[119]"/>).</p>

<p id="_a23a66bf-7177-5107-a298-830a081368d8">Radionuclidic impurities can be avoided, or at least minimized, during the production of a radionuclide source by choosing an optimal nuclear reaction with a pure target material. In spite of this, chemical purification is sometimes essential after the production. In any case, the contribution to the activity from the the radionuclidic impurities must be measured carefully. Any standard or certified source used in a metrology or quality assurance programme should be accompanied by certified values for the activities of its impurity components in addition to its nominal activity.</p>
2



008030half-life_​meas
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_fe6f8847-abc5-5ebd-9dd3-7d04c1f8c9a3" anchor="half-life_meas" obligation="normative">
<title id="_7a9db0bf-d4ca-3182-9080-2b45aec8f4c3">Half-life measurements</title>
<p id="_4159662e-b376-9d24-1026-ce7857a140a8">Direct decay measurements using an ionization chamber are the most obvious and least complicated means of determining the half-life of a radionuclide <eref type="inline" bibitemid="woo1990" citeas="[480]"/>. The equation for this method is given by the law of radioactive decay in <xref target="ionization_chamber"/>, <xref target="eq2-2"/>. Basically, the method consists in repeated measurements of activity values <asciimath>ii(A)(t)</asciimath> of the radionuclide under study as a function of time and a fit to the two parameters, namely the half-life <asciimath>ii(T)_(1//2)</asciimath> (or decay constant <asciimath>ii(lambda) = "ln"2//ii(T)_(1//2)</asciimath>) and an appropriate value for the initial activity <asciimath>ii(A)_"o" = ii(A)(t_"o")</asciimath>. In the decay method, <asciimath>ii(A)(t) = "d"ii(N)(t)//"d"t</asciimath> is defined as the probability of changing a defined nuclear state where <asciimath>ii(N)</asciimath> is the number of nuclides in this state <eref type="inline" bibitemid="icr1980" citeas="[226]"/>.</p>

<p id="_72bd5b0a-cef3-e064-a23a-bc5f8e5049a8">The half-life is assumed to be an innate parameter of a radionuclide and characteristic of its decay <eref type="inline" bibitemid="rut1902-2" citeas="[367]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="rut1903" citeas="[368]"/>. Its value may be slightly influenced by chemical effects (or interactions) in the case of electron capture nuclides, for which the electron density in the shell plays an important role. These chemical effects are normally of order 10<sup>–4</sup> of the actual half-life value of the capturing radionuclide. A survey of experimental and theoretical perturbation data of the decay constant (<asciimath>Delta ii(lambda)// ii(lambda)</asciimath>), including many references to historical publications of that problem, from about 1900, is given by Hahn et al. (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="hah1976" citeas="[194]"/>). Special techniques have been developed to measure these effects, for example differential experiments using two ionization chambers with samples of the same radionuclide in different physical or chemical states <eref type="inline" bibitemid="eme1972" citeas="[132]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="bog1974" citeas="[32]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="maz1975" citeas="[301]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="kak1975" citeas="[243]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="bog1976" citeas="[33]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="aum1979" citeas="[15]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="nir1981" citeas="[321]"/>. Kakiuchi et al. (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="kak1975" citeas="[243]"/>) also reported an application of this differential method for the measurement of a long half-life in a short period of time, e.g. with <sup>60</sup>Co in a 10 d run giving <asciimath>ii(T)_(1//2) = (5.27 +- 0.07)" a"</asciimath>.</p>
2



008302intercomparisons
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_feefd06a-925b-f6a6-729a-121730b13458" anchor="intercomparisons" obligation="normative">
<title id="_d29a7601-c61f-069d-43d5-0e72bc00550d">Intercomparisons and the International Reference System (SIR)</title>
<p id="_9147e03c-2786-05fe-eaf5-33cc3ac0ed70">The International Reference System, in French the “Système International de Référence”, abbreviated SIR, was conceived to complement and extend the international comparisons of activity measurements organized by the BIPM. The growing importance of accurate activity measurements in the 1960s led to the creation of a new section at the BIPM in 1961 which, among other duties, was charged with carrying out radionuclide measurements and intercomparisons. After discussions between the IAEA <eref type="inline" bibitemid="hou1970" citeas="[219]"/> and the BIPM, and taking advantage of previous experience with international comparisons, an ionization-chamber based measuring system for activity was installed at the BIPM in 1972 <eref type="inline" bibitemid="ryt1978a" citeas="[372]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="ryt1983b" citeas="[376]"/>. The task of the SIR is to maintain world-wide uniformity in activity measurements, to improve the accuracy of such measurements and to carry out quality control of national activity standards. In this way it ensures traceability to international standards. Since its creation, the SIR has given a most valuable service to the national standards laboratories which participate in its work by submitting solution standards for comparison <eref type="inline" bibitemid="ryt1985-2" citeas="[384]"/>.</p>

<p id="_d025d23a-d99f-5380-e13d-046af0545d99">The measurement procedures of the SIR, are described in <xref target="meas_equipment"/>. When applied to a particular sample they provide a value for the equivalent activity <asciimath>ii(A)_"e"</asciimath> of the particular photon-emitting radionuclide relative to a specific radium reference source. It is obvious that all the conditions for reproducibility and stability already discussed must be carefully observed when making measurements in the re-entrant ionization chambers of the SIR. As Houtermans (<eref type="inline" bibitemid="hou1970" citeas="[219]"/>) pointed out: “The essential quantity is <asciimath>ii(A)_"e"</asciimath>, i.e. the activity of the nuclide which gives the same instrument response as the long-lived standard, when measured under standard conditions.” The measured values <asciimath>ii(A)_"e"</asciimath>, together with statements of uncertainty and sample identification, are assembled and distributed annually to participants. The large number of radionuclides compared so far, shows the utility of activity measurements performed at an international level. It also shows the position of each participant with respect to the other. The system may help developing laboratories unable to perform direct activity measurements with particular radionuclides to link their ionization chamber measuring systems to international standards.</p>
2
